Since the interaction between HOB/BRB and HSA can be seen as isobaric processes, Van’t Hoff equation and Gibbs-Helmhotz equation (Eqs. (4)–(5) in SI) can be used to calculate thermodynamic parameters [16,17]. The plots of logK versus 1/T were carried out (Fig. 5
                        ), according to which the thermodynamic parameters were obtained (Table 1
                        ).

Circular dichroism (CD) spectra [22] were measured to quantitatively reveal the impact of HOB/BRB on albumin’s conformation [23] (Fig. 7
                        ). Transformed by Eqs. (6) and (7), CD data were employed to characterize alterations in albumin’s fine structure. Secondary structural contents of albumin with and with on addition of HOB/BRB were listed in Table 2
                        .
